Part I - (ProsperLoan Dataset)¶

by (Abbey Christian Banafo)¶

Introduction¶

This data is from Prosper.com, a money lendeng platform where people make money from those who borrow based on the interest rates.This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. See this data dictionary to understand the dataset's variables. In our case, we would want to know more about factors that may be responsible for borrowers to receive loan from this platform as well as the APR(Annual Percentage Rate) associated with it. Factors including the monthly income, the loan amounts, prosperscores which is a custom risk score built using historical Prosper data as well as other factors were most considerd during the exploration phase.

Cleaning¶

Quality Issues¶

Some Columns within the dataset seems to have large number of missing values hence, we would want to fill in those with the means and medians of their respective roles or use the calculations that leeds to such figures

Issue 1¶

Nan values in BorrowerAPR, EstimatedReturn, ProsperRatingAlpha, CreditGrades and EstimatedEffectiveyield columns.

BorrowerAPR

The BorrowerAPR values may be of interest and about 25 loans are missing this value. Because APR is equal to the borrower rate + fees, let's calculate the difference between the two and find the mean, and add that value to the borrower rate of our data missing an APR.

Define

  • Find difference between BorrowerAPR and BorrowerRate
  • Find the mean of the above
  • Fill null BorrowerAPR values with the mean Calculated

Coding and Testing

In [135]:
# Calculating the difference and mean for the APR
borrower_fees = loan["BorrowerAPR"] - loan["BorrowerRate"]
borrower_fees.mean()
Out[135]:
0.026041364737690028
In [136]:
# filling in null APR values with mean difference
loan["BorrowerAPR"].fillna(loan["BorrowerRate"] + borrower_fees.mean(), inplace=True)
loan["BorrowerAPR"].isnull().sum()
Out[136]:
0

EstimatedEffectiveYield

From the variable definitions, the effective yield is equal to the borrower interest rate (i) minus the servicing fee rate, (ii) minus estimated uncollected interest on charge-offs, (iii) plus estimated collected late fees which could be thought of as being equivalent to the borrower rate minus some expected loss from interest charge-offs and fees.

Define

  • Compute difference in BorrowerRate and the EstimatedEffectiveYield
  • Find the mean of the difference
  • Fill in null values with the mean

Coding and Testing

In [137]:
# filling null values with mean difference
estimated_loss_from_fees = loan["BorrowerRate"] - loan["EstimatedEffectiveYield"]
estimated_loss_from_fees.mean()
Out[137]:
0.027360274474679962
In [138]:
#  filling null values with mean difference
loan["EstimatedEffectiveYield"].fillna(loan["BorrowerRate"] - estimated_loss_from_fees.mean(), inplace=True)
loan["EstimatedEffectiveYield"].isnull().sum()
Out[138]:

EstimatedReturn

Again from the variables definitions, the EstimatedReturn is the difference between the EstimatedEffectiveYield and the EstimatedLoss Rate.

Define

  • Find the difference between the estimated yield and the estimated loss
  • Find the mean of the above
  • Fill in the null values with the mean above

Coding and Testing

Issue 2¶

Numbers as listing categories

The ListingCategory (numeric) column seems to give a false impression of being an ordinal Categorical Variable but is not hence would love to assign the actual names associated with the numeric variables assigned to it and thus rename it as ListingCategory as well. The column as well appears to be of type int hence would need to be coverted in a categorical data type.

Define

  • Replace all number with their appropriate Categories fromm the data dictionary
  • Covert the datatype to Categoric
  • Rename the column to ListingCategory.

Issue 8¶

Incorrect datatypes for some variables LoanStatus, ProsperScore,Occupation, ProsperRating (numeric) and others

  • In as much as the values for the ProsperScore column is numeric, the column by itself seems to be categoric as borrowers are given these numbers based on certain criteria. The numbers assigned also seems to have certain orders hence, exhibiting an ordinal type variable. As a result we would want to assign an order to this values as well
  • The loan status column would be a bit challenging as to considering it as being an ordinal of norminal type data. The Loan Status Column could be thought of as being Ordinal since persons who have completed may be considered better those current or overdue even though there could be futher questions as to when the loan was taken. Irrespective of all these analysis, we would want to consider this column as being a norminal type as current loanStatus persons is a bit confusing to FinalPamentInProgress cos one could be in both. The sum of the value counts of the different status was equivalent to the sum of th individual loanStatus groups but in reality one cannot tell the exact reason as to why they may be in that state hence we would consider this a norminal type data(without order).
  • The Occupation column seems categorical, hence would love to convert this column to a category datatype. The category is more likely to be of the norminal type of hence there would be no need for ordering.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There were 113,937 total loans given out for the original dataset. Of this, there are 81 unique variables depicting the condition and criteria for each loan. After cleaning the dataset however, ther happens to be 93,462 total loans with 52 columns that would be needed for our analysis. There seems to be more quantitative variables as compared to categorical types within the data.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

We would want to investigate the factors that may be responsible for lending out loan to members of the Prosper Loan Organization as well as the possible APR(Annual Percentage Rates) rates associated with them.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Factors such as the employment status, monthly income, BorrowerApr, loan lending records of borowers, Occupation, ProsperScore, Loan Amount, Recomendations could help determine the features interested in this dataset.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • The amount of loan lent out to borrowers was highly dependant on the monthly income of a borrower.
  • Monthly Incomes less than a region around \$8k were not given loans more than \$25k.
  • BorrowerAPR values was dependant on borrowers monthly income and as well the amount of money lent out to these borrowers.
  • ProsperScore values of borrowers seemed to be lower for borrowers with higher APR values.
  • Most borrowers had prosperscore between 4.0 and 8.0.
  • Most occupations seem to have monthly incomes within the \$10k range.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

  • The sudden rise in the amount that could be borrowed after passing the threshold monthly salary to be able to borrow more than \$25k seemed a bit odd.
  • Also, the large number of borrowers who took the loans for the purposes of associated to debt seems wierd as someone who is in dept could more like not able to refund back.

Conclusions¶

  • The aim for this exploration was to determine posible factors that could be responsible for lending out loan to members on the prosper platform. Variables such as the ProsperScore which is a custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score.
  • In finding out the factors that could affect the amount to be lent out to debtors, we looked at the distribution of members on how the loans were given out. We also looked at the distribution of the monthly income of these persons. A comparison between the distribution of the loan amount and the monthly income was generated. It was foundout borrowers with monthly incomes less than a region around \$8k were not given loans more than \$25k. Members with higher monthly income generally received higher loans. The occupations of these persons were hence compared to the monthly incomes to compare the distribution. The difference in monthly income did not vary that much with respect to the occupations of the borrowers. The borrowers generally received monthly income between a region slightly lower than \$1k to \$10k range. Since Occupation salaries did not vary that much it could only mean the amount loaned out to individuals were not so dependant on their occupations. Those who were doctors however seemed to have a wider range in terms of their salaries. The loan amounts was thus compared to the ListingCategories as well which in short terms was the reason for coming for the loan. It was found out borrowers usually came for loans as a result of dept, but the distribution of the loan amount was not so different for the dept categories as compared to the others. Hence could be concluded that one was more likely to receive a loan for reasons associated to dept in prosper. APR values also decreased with increase in prosperscores which was directly proportional to higher loan amounts as well
  • In a nutshell, we can say having a higher monthly income as well as using it for reasons related to dept in addition to having a high properscore is more likely to earn one a loan on the prosper platform. One is also more likely to have a lower interest rate with these factors as well.
